div.b:
*Docker has it's own internal network with it's own IP's &
ports that need to be exposed to the host to be
accessed (i.e. you can have container 1 exposed at port 5050
you will map it when running the container to a port on the host
so for example you might map host port 80 to 5050 and from there
if someone accesses port 80 on the host then it will be content from
container 1's port 5050)
